-- ── CVAT ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CVAT is a free, open-source, web-based tool for annotating images and video for computer vision and machine learning, with an optional managed SaaS and enterprise self-hosted edition.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source with Freemium SaaS tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$~50-65 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Palo Alto, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CVAT Review 2026: Features & Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CVAT is a free, open-source computer vision annotation tool for images and video. Compare self-hosted vs cloud pricing, features and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CVAT, short for Computer Vision Annotation Tool, is one of the most widely used open-source platforms for labeling images and video to train computer vision and machine learning models. The project began inside Intel in 2017, where computer vision engineers needed an efficient, web-based way to annotate large volumes of visual training data, and Intel released it publicly as an open-source project on GitHub in 2018. The tool quickly became a de facto standard in the computer vision community because it was free, browser-based, requiring no per-seat desktop installation, and purpose-built for the specific annotation shapes and workflows machine learning teams need, such as bounding boxes, polygons, polylines, points, cuboids, and skeletons, rather than being a general-purpose image editor adapted for labeling. For several years CVAT was stewarded jointly by Intel and the OpenCV Foundation, and it remains the officially recommended annotation tool of the OpenCV project. In 2022, the core team, including lead architect Nikita Manovich and CTO Boris Sekachev, both former Intel engineers, spun the project out into an independent company, CVAT.ai Corporation, headquartered in Palo Alto, California, to run the CVAT Online SaaS product and provide commercial enterprise support while keeping the underlying software open source.

CVAT's architecture separates cleanly into a free, self-hosted Community edition and a paid, cloud-hosted CVAT Online edition, both built on the same open-source codebase, licensed under the MIT License, available on GitHub. The self-hosted version can be deployed via Docker Compose on a company's own infrastructure at no license cost, giving organizations with sensitive data, such as medical imaging, defense, or autonomous vehicle footage, full control over where their training data lives, a major reason CVAT is popular in regulated industries. The platform supports images, video, and 3D point-cloud annotation; interpolation and object tracking across video frames; semi-automatic and automatic annotation using integrated AI and ML models; dataset import and export in all major machine learning formats including COCO, Pascal VOC, YOLO, and CVAT XML; and collaborative project and task management with role-based access control and a review-and-quality-control workflow for verifying annotation accuracy across a team.

For teams that don't want to operate their own infrastructure, CVAT.ai offers CVAT Online, a hosted SaaS version with a genuinely free tier including 1 GB storage, one project, and up to three tasks with community support, plus paid Solo and Team plans. The Solo plan runs roughly $33 per month billed monthly, or about $23 per month billed annually, including 25 GB of storage, ten projects, 250 tasks, API access with cloud-storage connections, and a monthly allotment of AI-assisted annotation calls. The Team plan is priced per user at the same rate with a minimum of two seats, scaling up to 50 users, and adds team collaboration, analytics and reporting, and role-based access controls. An Enterprise tier, starting at roughly $12,000 per year, offers CVAT hosted within a customer's own infrastructure with enhanced security, compliance support, and dedicated assistance, effectively a commercially supported version of the free self-hosted software for organizations that need vendor accountability and an SLA.

CVAT's core users are machine learning engineers, data scientists, and dedicated data-labeling teams building training datasets for object detection, image classification, semantic and instance segmentation, and video object tracking. It is used heavily in autonomous vehicle development, robotics, medical imaging, retail computer vision, agriculture, and academic research, where the combination of zero licensing cost, an active open-source community, and enterprise-grade features in the paid tiers covers the full range from solo researchers to large data-labeling operations. CVAT differentiates itself from proprietary annotation platforms such as Labelbox, Scale AI, SuperAnnotate, and V7 primarily through its open-source, self-hostable nature; teams that need full data sovereignty or want to avoid recurring per-seat SaaS costs at scale can run CVAT entirely on their own servers for free, something none of those primarily closed-source competitors offer to the same degree. Its closest open-source peers include Label Studio and Microsoft's now-largely-superseded Visual Object Tagging Tool, though CVAT is generally regarded as having stronger native video-annotation and interpolation tooling.

Community sentiment, reflected in its large GitHub star count and active issue tracker, is generally very positive about CVAT's annotation UX and format flexibility, with common critiques centering on the operational overhead of self-hosting at scale, which requires Docker and Kubernetes expertise, and a learning curve for teams unfamiliar with computer-vision annotation concepts. CVAT.ai Corporation continues to invest in AI-assisted, automatic-annotation features that use foundation vision models to pre-label data that annotators then only need to verify and correct, which is the primary lever the company and open-source community are using to reduce the labor cost of building large training datasets.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '0d4608fd-3411-46e9-b7bd-86e6765d726c';

