-- ── Cvent ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cvent is an enterprise event, meetings and webinar management platform used by event marketers and venues to plan, promote and execute in-person, virtual and hybrid events.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom / Enterprise (quote-based)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1999, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$5,000+ employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Tysons, Virginia, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cvent Review 2026: Features & Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cvent is an enterprise event management platform for in-person, virtual and hybrid events, webinars and venue sourcing. See features and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cvent is an enterprise-grade meetings, events, and hospitality technology platform used by corporate event marketers, associations, and hospitality venues to plan, promote, and execute in-person, virtual, and hybrid events at scale. The company was founded in 1999 by Reggie Aggarwal in the Washington, D.C. area and grew over two decades into one of the dominant platforms in the event-technology category, eventually reporting more than 5,000 employees and tens of thousands of customers worldwide. Cvent's headquarters remains in Tysons, Virginia. The company has gone through several notable ownership changes that reflect its scale: private-equity firm Vista Equity Partners acquired Cvent in 2016 for approximately $1.65 billion and took it private; in 2021 Cvent returned to the public markets through a merger with a special-purpose acquisition company, Dragoneer Growth Opportunities Corp II, at an enterprise value of roughly $5.3 billion; and in 2023, investment firm Blackstone completed a take-private acquisition of Cvent for approximately $4.6 billion, at $8.50 per share, with a minority investment from the Abu Dhabi Investment Authority and continued participation from Vista Equity Partners. Cvent has also grown through acquisition itself, including closing an acquisition of webinar platform ON24, extending its reach into standalone webinar and digital-engagement software.

Architecturally, Cvent is a broad suite rather than a single tool, organized around the full event lifecycle. Its core Event Management product covers event website and registration-page creation, largely template- and drag-and-drop-driven with some custom-code flexibility, attendee registration and payment processing, agenda and session management, speaker management, and email and marketing communications for promoting an event. Its onsite solutions layer, including Cvent OnArrival, handles physical event logistics such as badge printing, self-service and staffed check-in kiosks, attendance tracking, and lead retrieval for exhibitors. Cvent Webinar, built natively on the same platform and significantly expanded through the ON24 acquisition, provides studio-style virtual production tools such as custom backgrounds, multi-speaker layouts, and branded transitions so marketing teams can produce broadcast-quality webinars without a separate video-production vendor. A separate but connected product line, the Cvent Supplier Network, operates one of the largest online marketplaces for sourcing event venues and hotel room blocks, connecting meeting planners with tens of thousands of hotels and venues globally and letting planners submit requests for proposals and compare bids in one place, a business line that differentiates Cvent from most pure event-registration competitors. The platform also includes attendee engagement tools such as mobile event apps, networking and appointment-matching features, and sponsor and exhibitor portals, and integrates with major CRM and marketing-automation systems including Salesforce, Marketo, and HubSpot so that event-generated leads flow directly into a company's sales pipeline.

Cvent does not publish self-serve pricing; nearly all deployments are sold through direct sales with pricing customized to the modules purchased, such as event management, webinars, onsite check-in and badging hardware and software, and venue sourcing, and to the expected volume of events and attendees per year, which is standard practice for enterprise event-technology platforms serving corporations, associations, and higher-education institutions. This makes Cvent primarily an enterprise and mid-market tool rather than a self-service product for individuals or very small businesses running occasional one-off events; smaller or budget-conscious event organizers more commonly evaluate lighter-weight competitors like Eventbrite, Splash, Bizzabo, or Whova instead.

Cvent's target customers are corporate marketing and events teams running everything from small internal meetings to large-scale user conferences, professional associations and nonprofits organizing annual conferences, and hotels and venues that use the Cvent Supplier Network as a lead-generation and RFP-management channel. Enterprise buyers gravitate to Cvent specifically because few competitors offer the same breadth spanning registration, onsite badge and check-in hardware, venue sourcing, and webinar production inside one connected ecosystem with the compliance, security, and integration depth that large organizations require for procurement approval. The trade-off frequently cited in reviews on G2 and Capterra is that Cvent's platform can feel complex and require a steeper learning curve and longer implementation timeline than lighter, more modern point solutions, and that its lack of published pricing makes it harder to comparison-shop without engaging a sales representative.

Cvent hosts its own large annual user conference, Cvent CONNECT, where it typically previews major product announcements. The company continues to expand its AI capabilities across the platform, including AI-assisted event website and content creation and attendee-matching recommendations, mirroring the broader martech and event-tech industry's push toward generative AI tooling, while its core competitive moat remains the breadth of its connected event lifecycle and its large, incumbent hotel and venue sourcing marketplace, which is difficult for newer entrants to replicate.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'cbe1e28b-dacb-4d22-9f38-e5cc9dceeace';

