-- ── Cypht ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cypht is a free, open-source, lightweight webmail client that aggregates multiple email accounts, RSS feeds and calendars into one unified inbox.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cypht Review 2026: Features & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cypht is a free, open-source webmail client that unifies multiple email accounts, RSS feeds and calendars into one inbox. See features and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cypht is a free and open-source webmail client designed to give users a single, unified view across multiple email accounts, RSS feeds, and calendars, rather than forcing them to log into separate inboxes for each account. The project was created by developer Jason Munro, who had previously built the Hastymail and Hastymail 2 open-source webmail clients; Cypht, sometimes called HM3 or Hastymail 3, began as a from-scratch successor project, with its first public code commit dating to February 2014. It is distributed under the GNU Lesser General Public License version 2.1, meaning anyone can download, self-host, modify, and redistribute it without licensing fees, including for commercial purposes such as running it as a hosted service for customers. In June 2023, stewardship of the project formally shifted from being primarily driven by its original author to being run as a community project, with governance and contributions spread across the cypht-org GitHub organization and its contributors.

Technically, Cypht is written in PHP on the backend and JavaScript on the frontend, and it is explicitly designed to be lightweight, targeting low-resource servers and fast page loads rather than the heavier, more visually elaborate interfaces of webmail suites like Roundcube or SOGo. Architecturally, the application is built as a system of independent plugins the project calls module sets, which are executed by a small core framework; this plugin-based design is what allows Cypht to support multiple, disparate protocols and account types side by side. Supported protocols include IMAP and SMTP for traditional mail servers, JMAP, the newer JSON-based mail access protocol gaining adoption among modern mail providers like Fastmail, and EWS, or Exchange Web Services, for connecting to Microsoft Exchange and Office 365 accounts, a combination that lets a single Cypht installation aggregate accounts from very different backend mail systems into one interface. Beyond email, Cypht can pull in RSS and Atom feeds as another account type, displaying them alongside email messages in the same unified inbox, unread, sent, and flagged views. Additional built-in capabilities include a fast search engine that queries across all connected accounts and feeds simultaneously, support for Sieve mail-filtering rules that continue to apply server-side even when the user isn't actively logged in, LDAP directory lookups for contact and address-book integration, and auto-discovery of IMAP and SMTP server settings for popular email providers to simplify account setup.

Because Cypht has no company behind it and no commercial product tier, it has no founding company headquarters, employee count, or venture funding to report; it is maintained entirely as a community open-source project, hosted on GitHub, with no cost to download, install, or use. There is consequently no starting price beyond zero: any organization or individual can deploy Cypht on their own server, typically a LAMP or LEMP-style stack with PHP, at no licensing cost, though they bear their own hosting and maintenance costs. This makes Cypht conceptually similar in market position to other self-hosted open-source webmail clients such as Roundcube, SOGo, and Rainloop, rather than to commercial hosted email services like Gmail, Outlook.com, or Fastmail's own webmail interface, though Cypht can be configured to connect to and aggregate accounts from any of those providers via IMAP or JMAP.

Cypht's primary users are internet service providers offering webmail access to subscribers, schools and universities offering student and staff email portals, small businesses and self-hosters who want a lightweight, privacy-respecting alternative to commercial webmail, and individual power users who maintain several email accounts across different providers and want one aggregated inbox rather than switching between browser tabs or separate logins. Because it is open source and self-hosted, Cypht appeals particularly to privacy-conscious users and organizations that prefer not to route their mail through a third-party SaaS webmail provider. Reviews and community commentary consistently highlight Cypht's speed, low resource footprint, and multi-account aggregation as its standout strengths, while noting that its interface is intentionally minimal and less polished or feature-rich in areas like calendaring and contact management compared to heavier alternatives such as Roundcube or SOGo. Cypht is commonly deployed alongside Cyrus IMAP, Dovecot, or other IMAP servers as the web-facing mail client layer in self-hosted mail stacks, and its lightweight PHP footprint makes it a popular choice for VPS-hosted personal mail servers where minimizing memory and CPU usage matters. As an actively maintained but niche community project, Cypht does not compete for mainstream consumer webmail market share; instead it occupies a specific niche among self-hosted, developer- and sysadmin-oriented email deployments where lightweight performance and multi-protocol account aggregation are valued more than a full-featured groupware suite.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '665b1bfd-5f00-4b50-b428-2743e447dd31';

