-- ── Cyrus IMAP ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cyrus IMAP is a free, open-source, scalable email, calendar and contacts server used by ISPs, universities and enterprises to run their own mail infrastructure.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1994, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, USA (Carnegie Mellon University)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cyrus IMAP Review 2026: Features & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cyrus IMAP is a free, open-source, self-hosted IMAP/JMAP mail server built at Carnegie Mellon and maintained with Fastmail. See features and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cyrus IMAP is a free, open-source mail server that provides email, calendaring via CalDAV, contacts via CardDAV, and server-side filtering for organizations that want to run their own self-hosted mail infrastructure rather than relying on a third-party hosted email provider. The project originated at Carnegie Mellon University in the early-to-mid 1990s, with development tracing back to 1993 and 1994, as a replacement for CMU's earlier, locally built Andrew Mail System, which itself grew out of the university's Andrew Project. Cyrus was engineered from the outset for large-scale institutional deployment: CMU rolled it out to its entire incoming freshman class by 1998 and fully migrated its bulletin-board and mailing-list traffic onto Cyrus by the end of 2001, giving the software a multi-decade track record running production mail for tens of thousands of university mailboxes. Carnegie Mellon continues to host the project's infrastructure at cyrusimap.org and remains involved in its governance, though in the 2010s and 2020s the bulk of active day-to-day development has been carried out by engineers at Fastmail, the Australian email hosting company, which depends on Cyrus as the backend of its own commercial email service and therefore funds staff time specifically to develop, test, document, and maintain the project.

Architecturally, Cyrus is distinguished from many other IMAP server implementations, such as Dovecot or Courier, by its design philosophy of running on sealed servers, meaning regular end users never get shell or login access to the machine running the mail store, and all interaction happens exclusively through supported mail protocols. This design choice improves security and lets Cyrus store and index mail in its own optimized internal format rather than the more common Maildir or mbox formats used by other servers, which historically gave it strong performance and reliability advantages at very large scale, though it also means data is less directly portable outside Cyrus tooling. Cyrus supports IMAP and IMAPS, TLS-secured IMAP, POP3 and POP3S, KPOP, which is Kerberos-authenticated POP, and, increasingly central to the project's modern roadmap, JMAP, the newer JSON-based email protocol designed as a more efficient, web-friendly replacement for IMAP, which Fastmail co-authored and has driven adoption of in Cyrus. The server includes native support for Sieve, a standardized mail-filtering scripting language that lets users define server-side rules, for example auto-sorting or auto-responding to messages, that apply even when the user's mail client isn't running. Cyrus also implements access control lists on individual mailboxes for fine-grained sharing and delegation, per-user and per-hierarchy storage quotas, and full calendar and contacts support via the CalDAV and CardDAV protocols, effectively letting Cyrus function as a self-hosted groupware backend comparable in scope to Microsoft Exchange, rather than just an email store.

Because Cyrus is licensed permissively as open-source software under a BSD-style license and has no corporate parent selling licenses, it has no company headquarters, employee count, or commercial pricing plans in the traditional sense; it is free to download, deploy, and modify, with the cost to an organization being the infrastructure and systems-administration expertise required for self-hosting. Fastmail publishes some of its Cyrus-related engineering work publicly and periodically publishes commentary on the project's release and development plans, but Fastmail itself is a separate hosted-email company that uses Cyrus rather than selling Cyrus licenses. As of the mid-2020s the actively maintained stable release series is version 3.12, with 3.13 under active development and earlier series from 3.8 through 3.10 still receiving security patches.

Cyrus IMAP's target users are systems administrators, ISPs, universities, and enterprises that need to run mail at meaningful scale on their own infrastructure, often for reasons of data sovereignty, cost control at very large mailbox counts, regulatory compliance, or simply wanting full control over their email stack rather than depending on a third-party SaaS provider like Google Workspace or Microsoft 365. Because it requires genuine systems-administration expertise to install, configure, and operate, with no polished web-based setup wizard comparable to consumer software, Cyrus is not typically aimed at individual users or small businesses without dedicated IT staff; those users are better served by hosted providers or simpler self-hosted options.

Its closest open-source competitors are Dovecot, widely regarded as easier to configure and more commonly paired with separate mail transfer agents like Postfix in typical self-hosted setups, and Courier IMAP. Compared to Dovecot, Cyrus is generally seen as more oriented toward very large, centrally managed institutional deployments given its sealed-server model and native groupware features, whereas Dovecot has broader adoption among small-to-mid-size self-hosters. Front-end webmail clients such as Cypht, Roundcube, and SOGo are commonly deployed alongside Cyrus, or any IMAP server, to give end users a browser-based interface, since Cyrus itself is purely a backend server with no built-in web UI. Notable organizations and hosting providers beyond CMU and Fastmail that have relied on Cyrus over the years include a range of universities and ISPs for whom scalable, standards-compliant, self-hosted mail infrastructure has been a long-term operational requirement.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8e2764a7-0bfa-42fa-913d-469e0d66e4ce';

