-- ── D2 ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$D2 is a free, open-source, declarative diagram scripting language from Terrastruct that turns plain text into professional architecture and technical diagrams.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2022, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$D2 (D2lang) Review 2026: Features & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$D2 is a free, open-source diagram scripting language by Terrastruct that turns text into architecture diagrams. See features, licensing and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$D2, also known as D2lang, is an open-source declarative diagram scripting language that lets developers, architects, and technical writers describe diagrams as plain text and have a layout engine automatically render them as polished SVG, PNG, or PDF diagrams. It was created by Terrastruct, a small software company founded in 2019 by Alexander Wang and headquartered in San Francisco, California, whose core mission is building diagramming tools specifically for visualizing software architecture rather than general-purpose business diagrams. Terrastruct open-sourced D2 in November 2022 under the Mozilla Public License 2.0, a permissive but file-level-copyleft license that allows free commercial and non-commercial use, modification, and redistribution. Since its release, D2 has become one of the more actively adopted entrants in the growing diagrams-as-code category, joining tools like Mermaid, Graphviz and DOT, and PlantUML as a way to define diagrams in version-controllable plain text rather than through drag-and-drop GUI editors.

The core idea behind D2, reflected in its name, short for 'Declarative Diagramming,' is that authors describe what elements and relationships should exist in a diagram, for example defining shapes, connections, and labels in a simple text syntax, and D2's built-in layout engine automatically determines positioning, routing, and visual arrangement, rather than requiring the author to manually place every element as in tools like draw.io or Lucidchart. D2 ships with multiple selectable layout engines, including its own default engine, dagre, and an ELK-based engine for more complex graphs, so users can choose different auto-layout algorithms depending on diagram complexity and desired visual style. It includes a substantial shape library well suited to technical and infrastructure diagrams, including cylinders commonly used for databases, queues, clouds, and stick-figure person icons, alongside more conventional rectangles and containers, plus several official built-in visual themes, including dark-mode themes, so diagrams can be styled consistently without manual CSS-like styling work. Because D2 files are plain text, they are designed to live in the same Git repositories as the code and infrastructure they document: diagrams can be code-reviewed via pull requests, diffed to see exactly what changed between revisions, and kept in sync with a system's actual architecture far more easily than diagrams trapped in a separate proprietary GUI tool or binary file format.

D2 is used primarily as a command-line executable, available via Homebrew, direct binary download, Docker, or built from source in Go, the language D2 itself is implemented in, that compiles .d2 text files into SVG output, though it can also run as a server-side rendering service for integration into internal tools, documentation sites, or wikis. The language includes tooling aimed at developer workflows: an autoformatter for consistent style, a parser that can surface multiple syntax errors from a single broken file at once rather than stopping at the first error, syntax highlighting, and an official VS Code extension, alongside community-built integrations for Vim, Obsidian, Slack, Discord, Telegram, Emacs, and even a PostgreSQL schema importer that can auto-generate entity-relationship diagrams directly from a live database schema.

Because D2 the language and command-line tool are entirely free and open source, there is no cost to download, run, or embed D2 in personal or commercial projects, and Terrastruct does not charge for the core compiler. Terrastruct's commercial business is a separate, closely related product built around the D2 language that adds a visual, hybrid drag-and-drop-plus-text editing experience, real-time collaboration, and hosted diagram storage for teams, the paid product that funds the company's continued investment in the open-source language, in a business model similar to how companies like GitLab or Grafana Labs monetize a commercial layer around open-source cores. Terrastruct has stated it has not raised institutional venture funding, positioning itself as an independently operated company rather than a venture-backed startup chasing rapid growth.

D2's target users are software engineers, DevOps and platform engineers, solutions architects, and technical writers who need to create, and critically maintain, architecture diagrams, network topology diagrams, sequence diagrams, and infrastructure documentation as part of their normal code-centric workflow. It is a natural fit for teams already using docs-as-code practices, and its GitHub repository has attracted substantial community engagement, including stars, forks, and third-party plugin development, since its 2022 release, reflecting strong developer demand for text-based diagramming that produces genuinely attractive output rather than the more utilitarian look of some older ASCII- or Graphviz-based tools. Its closest direct competitors in the diagrams-as-code space are Mermaid, broadly popular due to native support in GitHub, GitLab, and Notion markdown rendering, and PlantUML, older and UML-focused, with D2 generally regarded as offering a more modern, more customizable visual output and a shape library specifically tuned for software-architecture diagrams, at the cost of being a newer, less universally pre-integrated tool than Mermaid. Compared to fully GUI-based tools like Lucidchart, draw.io, or Miro, D2's core value proposition is version-control-friendliness and reproducibility rather than free-form visual design flexibility.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8f5095fd-2fe0-49e0-936e-9bb82f1c6752';

